label chapter6:

    # [Scene: Pilot Site | Low Tide Morning]

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Driving, rhythmic percussion layered with rising strings]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The slap of boots in mud, quiet laughter, distant gulls; a motor idling far off, then muffled]
    "You are knee-deep in brackish mud, dark cargo pants soaked to the patched knees, sleeves rolled so you can feel the cold water curl around your wrists. The salt in the air is sharp enough that"
    "it stings the back of your throat; it smells of iron and old wood and the faint sweet of seaweed. Around you, everyone has their own small task and their own pace — a neighbor tightens"
    "oyster ropes, a kid darts in and out carrying a tray of plugs, Rosa hands out paper cups stacked with coffee and grilled tortillas."
    "Your hands move as if they remember what to do even before your brain catches up. Plant, tamp, anchor — the ritual of making. Each plug sinks and holds; the muddy resistance gives way and accepts"
    "the life you're asking it to carry. The work is noisy and honest, and in its noise is a kind of prayer."
    show eli_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    eli_navarro "It developed funny. Saltwater got in the corner, but—' (he shrugs) '—look at them, Maya. We actually made a little line."
    "You take the Polaroid. The image is smeared but the subject is clear: a crooked row of marsh plugs, string-swathed oysters, and, in the distance, the pier like a memory. Your thumb leaves another smear on the glossy face."
    "Internal: This is absurdly small. This is absurdly ours."

    menu:
        "Carefully wipe the Polaroid with your sleeve":
            "You drag your sleeve across the image, a streak of mud across the shore and the proof of it. Eli laughs, and the sound is the same as when you were kids — uncalculated, warm."
        "Tuck the Polaroid into your notebook pocket instead":
            "You slide the photo into your field notebook, between Asha's notes and the sketch of the pier. The paper sticks slightly; the moment is saved in a private fold. Eli bumps your shoulder with his in a soft, satisfied nudge."

    # --- merge ---
    "The narrative continues."
    "Eli leans in, watching the smear of your fingers on the Polaroid, eyes bright."

    eli_navarro "We should hang that at Rosa's. Make it a thing people can see. Proof beats promises, every time."
    show maya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "Yeah. Put it next to Tomas's flyer about repair hours. Make it obvious that something changed not because of a contract but because people showed up."
    "Eli presses the heel of his hand to your shoulder, mud-smudged and sure."

    eli_navarro "We showed up. You showed up. So did they."
    "The pressure from his hand is small, constant — a kind of compass you can trust."
    # [Scene: Pier | Mid-Morning]
    hide eli_navarro
    hide maya_reyes

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Brass and strings; tempo accelerates into a buoyant, urgent cadence]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Camera shutters, the murmur of conversation rising to organized sound, a truck door slamming in the distance; engines hum then stutter]
    "Councilor Marco watches the living shoreline work in progress. His posture is hesitant — not hostile, but the way someone surveys a structure they're used to designing from blueprints rather than by hand. He clears his throat."
    show councilor_marco_lin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    councilor_marco_lin "Ms. Reyes — the engineering team will be preparing a formal assessment. I don't want to discount this—' (he gestures vaguely, indicating the work and the people) '—but we need to be certain it's scalable, safe. The town's safety is my responsibility."
    "A murmur runs through the group like a tide-line. You feel the old muscle memory of public meetings: the careful parsing of words, the measured steps, the pressure of accountability. But today the room smells of"
    "frying garlic and the hands that made the breakfast; safety here is argued with soil and faces."
    "You fold your wet hands together before answering. The compass on your cord swings against your sternum."
    show maya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "Councilor — this is scalable. It was designed with modularity in mind. Asha's sensors are proving energy attenuation already. But it's not just the data. It's trust. It’s neighbors knowing their shoreline can be shaped by them and for them."
    "Marco's gaze flicks to the sensor readouts, to the lab tags, then back to Rosa, who is smiling as she refills a tray. His expression loosens, a fraction."

    councilor_marco_lin "You have evidence, and you have community buy-in. Those are powerful together. But there are liabilities. There are standards."

    maya_reyes "Then let's meet the standards together. We will document, iterate, bring in the expertise. We won't let care for our ecology be an excuse for inaction, and we won't let fear stop the work."
    show asha_malik at center:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_malik "Marco — hybrid approaches have to start somewhere. You can fund the assessment, the lab can provide continuous monitoring, and the town can provide the labor and the lived knowledge. That is how resilience like this scales — from the ground up and the top down."
    "Councilor Marco exhales, visibly calculating, then looks toward the pier where Tomas is kneeling, tamping the soil into a plug with stubborn focus. Tomas's jaw works as he compacts the earth exactly the way he used to hammer nails into boards."
    hide councilor_marco_lin
    show tomas_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    tomas_reyes "Councilor — I'm signing to stay. I don't have much money, but I have my hands. I want my kids to know this place the way I do. If the town can help—if we can make this work—I'm in."

    "The sound is small but it lands like a bell. Around you, heads turn. Camera phones are lifted. Rosa starts a chant of support that ripples outward" "Stay! Stay! Stay!"

    menu:
        "Step closer and clasp Tomas's shoulder":
            "You lean in, mud squelching beneath your boot, and squeeze his shoulder. His knuckles go white for a second. He looks up at you, brows knit in that old way, and there is a fierce, gratefully surprised smile."
        "Stand back and let Tomas make his statement alone":
            "You step back, letting the moment belong to him. Tomas meets your eyes across the distance and gives a quick, private nod, as if acknowledging a debt you both share."

    # --- merge ---
    "The moment resolves and Tomas signs the statement."
    "Tomas reaches for a clipboard where a simple statement is written — 'Intent to stay & adapt' — and signs with a hand that trembles a little at first, then steadies. The paper creases under his palm. The moment of decision scrapes and then settles."
    "Eli catches your eye from the edge of the crowd. He weaves through people and stands beside you, breath warm, face earnest."
    hide maya_reyes
    show eli_navarro at right:
        zoom 0.7

    eli_navarro "You did this. We did this. It's not perfect, and it won't stop every storm, but—' (he searches for the word and finds it) '—it works."
    hide asha_malik
    show maya_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "It buys time, and it builds the capacity to do more. It changes the narrative. That's what matters."

    eli_navarro "And it changes things for us."

    maya_reyes "Then we'll keep designing. We'll keep planting. We'll keep measuring and improving."
    "Eli squeezes your shoulder in a steady, tactile punctuation. The world narrows for a pulse of breath."
    # [Scene: Community Spaces | Noon]
    hide tomas_reyes
    hide eli_navarro
    hide maya_reyes

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Full orchestra swells into a bright, triumphant major chord]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Engines stop; a long metallic clink from across the bay. Someone shouts. Cheer rises.]
    "Across the water, muffled by salt and distance, the cadence of heavy machinery stutters and then — noticeably, audibly — quiets. The rumble of a crawler that had been cutting toward Aurelia's site ceases; a driver"
    "leans out, phone in hand, watching screens. A small, stunned silence follows before the crowd bursts into a complex sound: disbelief, then applause, then the shouts and clapping of people who had come not to a"
    "meeting but to make something."
    show rosa_alvarez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_alvarez "Look! Even the machines are listening."
    "Neighbors whooped. Someone set off a pocket-sized confetti popper; bits of wet paper glittered in the sun and stuck to boots and cheeks."
    "Councilor Marco steps forward, the lines of his face softened by something like concession. He reaches for the microphone that had been sitting on the table, unused."
    show councilor_marco_lin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    councilor_marco_lin "I told you we needed proof. This is proof. Not only are the readings promising, but the community has rallied. I—' (he looks out at the people who have given their morning and their backs to the mud) '—I will propose a phased rollout of the pilot, with formal monitoring and standards. We will draft an assessment and see how to fund scaling. I—and the council—will stand behind the town."
    "The crowd's reaction is immediate and loud: relief, cheering, tears on more than one face. You feel like your heart might cavitate with the speed of it — joy so bright it hurts."
    "Internal: Guilt, that familiar tether, loosens by fractions. Not gone. Not ever. But smaller. Rechanneled into this: proof, practical care, stubbornness made communal."
    "Eli steps close, and when he squeezes your shoulder it is as though he transfers warmth into you."
    show eli_navarro at center:
        zoom 0.7

    eli_navarro "Come on. Let's celebrate the ridiculousness of us."
    "You laugh — a clean, surprised sound — and the laugh turns into a thing that others join. Tomas laughs too, and for a moment your brother looks younger, free of a worry that had lived under his jaw for months."
    "You walk to the table where the clipboards are stacked. A volunteer photographer — camera dangling — angles for a crowd shot and signals you both. He calls out cheerfully."

    "Photographer" "Hold that together, folks! Let me get the 'before they try to corporate-it' shot!"
    "You and Eli press close. Your arms touch; mud-slick palms brush. He leans his forehead against yours for a beat, a public intimacy but private at the same time."

    eli_navarro "We promise to keep going, right? Not just the pilot, but the work after the press leaves."
    hide rosa_alvarez
    show maya_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "Promise. With measures, with community oversight, with Asha checking every batch of sensors. And with you."

    eli_navarro "(half-teasing, half-solemn) And with you."

    menu:
        "Pull Eli close and kiss him — quick and messy":
            "You close the tiny distance and press your mouth to his in a brief, mud-tangy kiss. It's imperfect and immediate; when you part you both laugh, breathless and a little stunned by having made the private public."
        "Take Eli's hand and keep your foreheads together":
            "You lace your fingers with his, thumbs finding familiar calluses. The gesture says everything that a kiss might, only steadier: we will work, together."
        "Whisper 'thank you' and step back to address the crowd":
            "You whisper the words and step back, taking the space to speak to the people who built this morning. They look at you with exhaustion and exhilaration and you feel like a conduit for something larger."

    # --- merge ---
    "The chosen moment seals the morning; the scene continues."
    "You choose the small thing that fits you best — the tactile, the shared breath, the public vow — and whatever you pick lands like a seal on the morning."
    "The music swells. Children run between feet, laughing, their bare ankles smeared; Rosa hands out second helpings of tortillas topped with something spicy and bright; Asha moves through the people, checking sensors, smiling at readings that climb on her tablet."
    "The actuality of it — the pilot standing where the ocean meets the town, community hands in the mud, an argument for a different future made tangible — feels like the most honest kind of victory there is: messy, communal, built by people whose stakes are real."
    "You watch Tomas sign a small addendum to a local pledge — nothing legally ironclad but everything socially binding. He folds the paper, tucks it into his sweatshirt pocket, and for a second, looks like the kid who once ran the pier boards barefoot."

    "Tomas Reyes (to you, quietly)" "Maya — thanks."

    "Maya Reyes (gruff with emotion)" "Don't thank me. Thank all of us."
    "He bumps your hip with his shoulder in that half-annoyed, half-admiring way that is grammar when it comes from family."
    "Eli slips an arm around your waist, and the two of you stand like that for a beat — in the middle of sound and motion, anchored."

    eli_navarro "We'll learn. We'll adapt. We'll keep the records, we'll file the reports, we'll host the volunteers. We'll do the paperwork too. Promise."

    maya_reyes "I promise. And I'll keep Asha's notes close, and I'll keep Tomas fed, and…"

    eli_navarro "And you'll keep me honest."

    maya_reyes "And you'll keep me hopeful."
    "The promise is perfunctory and also real; it is an utterance that ties two practical hearts to a seasonal labor of love."
    hide councilor_marco_lin
    hide eli_navarro
    hide maya_reyes

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A resolving chord, bright and sustained; the percussion slows to a heartbeat]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The tide pulls at the new line, silt whispering; distant horns sound once, long and soft]
    "You feel your chest loosen in a way that isn't about relief alone. It's the uncoiling of something that has been taut for too long: guilt, fear, the sense that a single mistake could mean rubble."
    "It's replaced now — not by certainty, but by the steadier muscle of collective care."
    "Internal: This pilot won't stop all storms. It won't make every lost home return. But it proves a rhythm: the town can act; care can be engineered into survival. That is political weight. That is love."
    "You tuck the smudged Polaroid back into your notebook if you hadn't already, or you pin it to Rosa's board for everyone to see. Either way, it will be there — damp, imperfect, true."
    "Eli squeezes your shoulder. The warmth is steady; it feels like a column of support you can lean on when the nights are cold and the data is ambiguous."
    "You look out over the line you've helped build. Children clamber on the tidal rocks and squeal as a small wave nudges the new plantings; an elder murmurs a connection between the old pier piles and the new oyster lines; Councilor Marco shakes hands and takes notes."
    "You breathe in the smell of salt and smoke and frying garlic, and for the first time in a while that feeling of watchful dread eases into something you can hold with both hands: hope that is earned, not naive; a partnership that is both personal and practical."

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Soft piano, a single sustaining note that resolves slowly]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A single gull cries out; distant applause]
    "You let out a long breath and — even though there will be council meetings to file, permits to wrangle, and storms to weather — you allow yourself, for one slow second, to feel that what you did today matters."

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_6 at full_bg
